<HEADLINE>
E.U. VOICES CONCERN OVER CHINA'S HUMAN RIGHTS RECORD
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, Belgium, April 26 (CNA) 04/27/07  11:43:32 (By P.C.
Tang and Y.F. Low)
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament adopted Thursday its 2006 annual report
on human rights in the world, in which the parliament expressed
concern about the situation in China.
</P>
<P>
The report, adopted during the parliament's plenary session held
in Strasbourg, France, said China's human rights record remains a
matter of "serious concern" and should "receive more focus in the
build-up to the Beijing Olympic games."
</P>
<P>
The report emphasized the need to strengthen and improve the
human rights dialogue  between the European  Union and China,
suggesting that the question of Tibet be raised in talks with
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the report said the European Union's trade relations
with China should be contingent upon human rights reform.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report also expressed "deep concern regarding the
deterioration of the human rights situation" in Iran, especially
the intensification of the repression against human rights
defenders.
</P>
<P>
On the human rights situation in Russia, the report expressed
regret that the European Union has had only limited success in
bringing about policy change.
</P>
